Package io.sourceforge.curtthomas.isbn

Enum Isbn

java.lang.Object
java.lang.Enum<Isbn>
io.sourceforge.curtthomas.isbn.Isbn
All Implemented Interfaces:
Serializable, Comparable<Isbn>, java.lang.constant.Constable
public enum Isbn
extends Enum<Isbn>
Constants corresponding to the data at https://www.isbn-international.org/range_file_generation.

International Standard Book Numbers comprise at most fifteen distinct characters (the letters that form the acronym ISBN itself [optionally], the Roman numeral X, and the digits 0-9), and can remain as intelligible in the context of source code as they already are all around the world. Accordingly, the terminological conventions on which the following documentation relies are minimal:

  • "ISBN" is used exclusively as an acronym for International Standard Book Number.
  • "isbn" (initial lower-case letter) is used exclusively as the name of a method parameter
  • "Isbn" (initial upper-case letter) is used in reference to this type, preferably in the context of the constants and (particularly, static) methods that it defines and the bytecode that is generated once that it is compiled.
  • "AGENCY constant" refers to constants defined herein that are returned when the class's static assignAgencyConstant() method is called.
  • "RANGE constant" refers to constants defined herein that are returned when the class's static assignRangeConstant() method is called.
  • The word "component" can be expected to pertain to the constants PREFIX, PREFIX_OLD, AGENCY_NAME, REGISTRANT_ELEMENT, PUBLICATION_ELEMENT, CHECK_DIGIT, REGISTRANT_ELEMENT_SIZE, REGISTRANT_ELEMENT_EXTENT, PUBLICATION_ELEMENT_SIZE, and PUBLICATION_ELEMENT_EXTENT.
  • "AGENCY" and "RANGE" also identify constants, as does "COMPONENT".
Attributes possessed by AGENCY constants (e.g., ENGLISH_LANGUAGE_0)) always ever determine the respective values of PREFIX, PREFIX_OLD, and AGENCY_NAME, while the attributes of each RANGE constant (e.g. ENGLISH_LANGUAGE_0__00_TO_19_RANGE) determine the respective values of REGISTRANT_ELEMENT, PUBLICATION_ELEMENT, REGISTRANT_ELEMENT_SIZE, REGISTRANT_ELEMENT_EXTENT, PUBLICATION_ELEMENT_SIZE, and PUBLICATION_ELEMENT_EXTENT.

The Isbn type's static methods usually accept ISBNs as their parameters. The only static methods that do not are overloaded versions of the values() method added automatically when the type was compiled. With the exception of getComponent(), the remaining methods do not accept parameters, and are only called directly from constants.

Author:
Curt Selak

    Modifier and Type Method Description
    static TreeMap<String,​String> allComponentsAddedKeys​(String isbn)
    Furnishes a sorted map containing the corresponding data for the International Standard Book Number passed as an argument.
    static String[][][] allComponentsAsArray​(String... isbns)
    Furnishes the different parts of one or more ISBNs as a multidimensional array.
    static String allComponentsAsJson​(boolean newlines, String... isbns)
    Calls allComponentsMinKeys() and subsequently produces a String in JSON format; if multiple parameters are passed, a JSON string is produced for each.
    static String allComponentsAsJson​(String... isbns)
    Calls allComponentsMinKeys() and subsequently produces a String in JSON format; if multiple parameters are passed, a JSON string is produced for each.
    static TreeMap<String,​String> allComponentsMinKeys​(String isbn)
    Furnishes a sorted map containing the corresponding data for the International Standard Book Number passed as an argument; omits two of the keys produced when allComponentsAddedKeys() is called instead.
    static Isbn assignAgencyConstant​(String isbn)
    Locates the constant uniquely corresponding to an ISBN's agency prefix.
    static Isbn assignRangeConstant​(String isbn)
    Locates the constant uniquely corresponding to the range within which an ISBN's registrant element occurs, respective to the code for the agency responsible for assigning the registrant element.
    int extent()
    Supplies the maximum number of registrant elements/publisher prefixes that a given agency can currently assign according to RangeMessage.xml.
    Isbn getAgencyConstant()
    Called by constants that assignRangeConstant() returns (RANGE constants) in order to obtain the corresponding type of constant that assignAgencyConstant() returns (an AGENCY constant); in other words, called by a RANGE constant (i.e., a constant that returns RANGE when it calls getContext()) in order to obtain an AGENCY constant (i.e., a constant that returns AGENCY when it calls getContext()).
    static String getAgencyName​(String isbn)
    Accepts an ISBN in 10-digit or 13-digit format as input and returns a String consisting of the name that occurs in RangeMessage.xml's Agency element.
    static String getCheckDigit​(String isbn)
    Accepts an ISBN in 10-digit or 13-digit format as input and returns a String consisting of the check digit.
    String getComponent​(String isbn)
    A method overridden by constants returned by assignAgencyConstant() (AGENCY constants) and constants that return Isbn.COMPONENT when they call getContext() (COMPONENT constants).
    Isbn getContext()
    Supplies the caller's corresponding CONTEXT constant: (AGENCY, RANGE, COMPONENT, or CONTEXT).
    int getMaximumAssigned()
    Called principally by constants returned by assignRangeConstant() (RANGE constants) in order to determine the number of prefixes available in a given range.
    static String getPrefix​(String isbn)
    Accepts an ISBN in 10-digit or 13-digit format as input and returns a String consisting of the agency's prefix preceded by the EAN/UCC prefix.
    static String getPrefixOld​(String isbn)
    Accepts an ISBN in 10-digit or 13-digit format as input and returns a String consisting of the agency's prefix without the EAN/UCC prefix that 13-digit ISBNs incorporate.
    static String getPublicationElement​(String isbn)
    Accepts an ISBN in 10-digit or 13-digit format as input and returns a String consisting of the portion of the ISBN occurring in between the registrant element and the check digit.
    static String getPublicationElementExtent​(String isbn)
    Accepts an ISBN in 10-digit or 13-digit format as input and returns a String indicating the maximum number of times the ISBN's registrant element/publisher prefix can be used.
    static int getPublicationElementExtentAsInt​(String isbn)
    Accepts an ISBN in 10-digit or 13-digit format as input and returns an int indicating the maximum number of times the ISBN's registrant element/publisher prefix can be used.
    static String getPublicationElementSize​(String isbn)
    Accepts an ISBN in 10-digit or 13-digit format as input and returns a String indicating the number of digits in (length of) the publication element.
    static int getPublicationElementSizeAsInt​(String isbn)
    Accepts an ISBN in 10-digit or 13-digit format as input and returns an int indicating the number of digits in (length of) the publication element.
    static String getQualifiedRegistrantElement​(String isbn)
    Accepts an ISBN in 10-digit or 13-digit format as input and returns a String consisting of a concatenation of the prefix and the registrant element.
    static String getRegistrantElement​(String isbn)
    Accepts an ISBN in 10-digit or 13-digit format as input and returns a String consisting of the portion of the ISBN that identifies the publisher (i.e., the registrant prefix).
    static String getRegistrantElementExtent​(String isbn)
    Accepts an ISBN in 10-digit or 13-digit format as input and returns a String indicating the length of the range to which the registrant element belongs; in effect, the maximum number of registrants who can be assigned to the range in which the registrant element of the ISBN that is to hand falls.
    static int getRegistrantElementExtentAsInt​(String isbn)
    Accepts an ISBN in 10-digit or 13-digit format as input and returns an int indicating the length of the range to which the registrant element belongs; in effect, the maximum number of registrants who can be assigned to the range in which the registrant element of the ISBN that is to hand falls.
    static String getRegistrantElementSize​(String isbn)
    Accepts an ISBN in 10-digit or 13-digit format as input and returns a String indicating the number of digits in (length of) the registrant element (publisher prefix).
    static int getRegistrantElementSizeAsInt​(String isbn)
    Accepts an ISBN in 10-digit or 13-digit format as input and returns an int indicating the number of digits in (length of) the registrant element (publisher prefix).
    static String isbnThirteen​(String isbn)
    Called each and every time the Isbn type begins performing an operation that concerns one or more of an ISBN's components.

    • values

      public static Isbn[] values​(Isbn... flags)
      Overloads the values() method added to the Isbn type once that it was compiled in order to filter the constants.
      Parameters:
      flags - One or more of Isbn.CONTEXT, Isbn.AGENCY, Isbn.RANGE, or Isbn.COMPONENT.

      • Parameters that are AGENCY constants (constants returned by assignAgencyConstant()), RANGE constants (constants returned by assignRangeConstant()), or constants that return COMPONENT when they call getContext() are ignored.
      • If identical parameters are passed, the duplicates are preserved not discarded:
                                        Isbn[] unique = Isbn.values(Isbn.AGENCY); //unique.length is 257
				Isbn[] redundant = Isbn.values(Isbn.AGENCY,Isbn.AGENCY); //redundant.length is 514
        The length of the array returned by the values() method furnished by the compiler and called by the overloaded versions only ever remains the same throughout runtime.
      Returns:
      • Returns an array of Isbn constants the length of which ultimately depends on the parameters passed.
      • Returns an array of zero length if only constants of the respective types returned by either assignAgencyConstant() (AGENCY constants) or assignRangeConstant() (RANGE constants), or constants that return COMPONENT when they call getContext(), are passed as parameters.
      See Also:
      values(Comparator comparator,Isbn... flags)

    • values

      public static Isbn[] values​(Comparator<Isbn> comparator, Isbn... flags)
      Overloads the values() method added to the Isbn type once that it was compiled in order to filter the constants, and sorts the result prior to returning it.

      For example:

                                      Comparator<Isbn> nonordinal = (a,b) -> a.name().compareTo(b.name());
				Isbn[] constantsAtoZ = Isbn.values(nonordinal, Isbn.CONTEXT);
      produces [AGENCY,COMPONENT,CONTEXT,RANGE], where values() called only with the flags parameter would have produced [AGENCY,RANGE,COMPONENT,CONTEXT].
      Parameters:
      comparator - A Comparator type.
      flags - One or more of Isbn.CONTEXT, Isbn.AGENCY, Isbn.RANGE, or Isbn.COMPONENT.

      • Parameters that are AGENCY constants (constants returned by assignAgencyConstant()), RANGE constants (constants returned by assignRangeConstant()), or constants that return COMPONENT when they call getContext() are ignored.
      • If identical parameters are passed, the duplicates are preserved not discarded:
                                        Comparator<Isbn> nonordinal = (a,b) -> a.name().compareTo(b.name()); 
				Isbn[] unique = Isbn.values(nonordinal, Isbn.AGENCY); //unique.length is 257
				Isbn[] redundant = Isbn.values(nonordinal, Isbn.AGENCY,Isbn.AGENCY); //redundant.length is 514
        The length of the array returned by the values() method furnished by the compiler and called by the overloaded versions only ever remains the same throughout runtime.
      Returns:
      • Returns an array of Isbn constants the length of which ultimately depends on the parameters passed. The assignment of the constants' respective indexes ultimately is determined by the Comparator type passed as the first parameter.
      • Returns an array of zero length if only constants of the respective types returned by either assignAgencyConstant() (AGENCY constants) or assignRangeConstant() (RANGE constants), or constants that return COMPONENT when they call getContext(), are passed as parameters.
      See Also:
      values(Isbn... flags), extent(), getMaximumAssigned(), ranges()

    • getContext

      public Isbn getContext()
      Supplies the caller's corresponding CONTEXT constant: (AGENCY, RANGE, COMPONENT, or CONTEXT).
      Returns:
      • Returns CONTEXT if the caller is AGENCY, RANGE, COMPONENT, or CONTEXT itself.
      • Returns COMPONENT if the caller is PREFIX, PREFIX_OLD, AGENCY_NAME, REGISTRANT_ELEMENT, PUBLICATION_ELEMENT, CHECK_DIGIT, REGISTRANT_ELEMENT_SIZE, REGISTRANT_ELEMENT_EXTENT, PUBLICATION_ELEMENT_SIZE, or PUBLICATION_ELEMENT_EXTENT,
      • Returns RANGE if the caller's name ends with the String "RANGE",
      • Returns AGENCY otherwise, including when the caller is UNKNOWN.
      See Also:
      getAgencyConstant(), ranges(), values(Isbn... flags), values(Comparator comparator,Isbn... flags), CONTEXT, AGENCY, RANGE, COMPONENT

    • assignAgencyConstant

      public static Isbn assignAgencyConstant​(String isbn)
      Locates the constant uniquely corresponding to an ISBN's agency prefix.

      Because access to the API can depend on access to the constants it defines, the assignAgencyConstant() and assignRangeConstant() methods are of some little importance as entry points. An example elsewhere in this documentation defined an array of three ISBNS, the respective agency prefixes of which were 978-0, 978-2, and 978-3:

                              String[] isbns = {"0415083699","2738424155","3518576348"};
			Arrays.sort(isbns); //still ["0415083699","2738424155","3518576348"]
      Above, sorting the array was necessary only in order to demonstrate that the array indexes already were assigned to the String objects based on their natural order. Calling assignAgencyConstant() introduces other possibilities where the criteria for sorting are concerned:
                              Comparator<String> comparator = 
			(a,b) -> 
			Integer.valueOf(Isbn.assignAgencyConstant(a).extent())
			.compareTo(Integer.valueOf(Isbn.assignAgencyConstant(b).extent()));
			Arrays.sort(isbns, comparator); //isbns is now ["3518576348","2738424155","0415083699"]
      The array was sorted a second time in ascending order, but the key was assigned to a characteristic of each ISBN number's corresponding AGENCY constant, namely the number of possible registrant elements (publisher prefixes) available within it to assign: 250,453 for 978-3, 568,126 for 978-2, and 579,052 for 978-0. Respective calls to assignAgencyConstant() were each chained to a call to the Isbn type's nonstatic extent() method in order to produce the key.
      Parameters:
      isbn - An International Standard Book Number in either 10-digit or 13-digit format.
      Returns:
      A constant defined by the Isbn type, the identifier of which consists of the agency name, concatenated where necessary with an ordinal number. For example, the following code
       
                        Isbn.assignAgencyConstant("3499290111");
      returns GERMAN_LANGUAGE.

      The type of the value returned is Isbn, not String. In order to obtain a String object, the following is necessary:

                              Isbn.assignAgencyConstant("3499290111").name();
      The call to the constant's inherited name() method returns "GERMAN_LANGUAGE".
      See Also:
      assignRangeConstant(String isbn), extent(), ranges()

    • ranges

      public Isbn[] ranges()
      Supplies the calling AGENCY constant's applicable RANGE constants as an array.

      For example, Isbn.LEBANON_1.ranges()[1] returns LEBANON_1__10_TO_39_RANGE.

      Returns:
      • If the caller is an AGENCY constant, returns an array containing one RANGE constant for each of the caller's applicable ranges.
      • Returns an empty Isbn array if the caller is a RANGE, COMPONENT, or CONTEXT constant.
      See Also:
      extent(), getAgencyConstant()

    • extent

      public int extent()
      Supplies the maximum number of registrant elements/publisher prefixes that a given agency can currently assign according to RangeMessage.xml.

      Returns:
      • When called by an AGENCY constant, returns an int representing the maximum number of registrant elements (publisher prefixes) that the AGENCY constant can encompass. Isbn.LEBANON_0.extent(), for example, returns 6940.
        • When called by Isbn.UNKNOWN, returns 0.
      • Returns -1 when called by a RANGE, COMPONENT, or CONTEXT constant.
      See Also:
      ranges(), getMaximumAssigned(), AGENCY

    • assignRangeConstant

      public static Isbn assignRangeConstant​(String isbn)
      Locates the constant uniquely corresponding to the range within which an ISBN's registrant element occurs, respective to the code for the agency responsible for assigning the registrant element.

      Because access to the API can depend on access to the constants it defines, the assignRangeConstant() and assignAgencyConstant() methods are of some little importance as entry points. An example elsewhere in this documentation defined an array of three ISBNS, the respective agency prefixes of which were 978-0, 978-2, and 978-3:

                              String[] isbns = {"0415083699","2738424155","3518576348"};
			Arrays.sort(isbns); //still ["0415083699","2738424155","3518576348"]
      Above, sorting the array was necessary only in order to demonstrate that the array indexes already were assigned to the String objects based on their natural order. Calling assignRangeConstant() introduces other possibilities where the criteria for sorting are concerned:
                              Comparator<String> comparator = 
			(a,b) -> 
			Integer.valueOf(Isbn.assignRangeConstant(a).getMaximumAssigned())
			.compareTo(Integer.valueOf(Isbn.assignRangeConstant(b).getMaximumAssigned()));
			Arrays.sort(isbns, comparator); //isbns is now ["0415083699","3518576348","2738424155"]
      The array was sorted a second time in ascending order, but the key was assigned to a characteristic of each ISBN number's corresponding RANGE constant, namely the number of possible registrant elements (publisher prefixes) available to assign given the specific range's bounds: 269 for ENGLISH_LANGUAGE_0__370_TO_638_RANGE, 500 for GERMAN_LANGUAGE__200_TO_699_RANGE, and 1400 for FRENCH_LANGUAGE__7000_TO_8399_RANGE. Respective calls to assignRangeConstant() were each chained to a call to the Isbn type's nonstatic getMaximumAssigned() method in order to produce the key.
      Parameters:
      isbn - An International Standard Book Number in either 10-digit or 13-digit format.
      Returns:
      A constant defined by the Isbn type, the identifier of which consists of the agency name, concatenated where necessary with an ordinal number, followed by two further underscore characters, followed by a concatenation of the lower bound of the range, the word "TO", the upper bound of the range, and the word "RANGE". For example, the following code
                              Isbn.assignRangeConstant("3499290111");
      returns GERMAN_LANGUAGE__200_TO_699_RANGE.

      The type of the value returned is Isbn, not String. In order to obtain a String object, the following is necessary:

                              Isbn.assignRangeConstant("3499290111").name();
      The call to the constant's inherited name() method returns "GERMAN_LANGUAGE__200_TO_600_RANGE".
      See Also:
      getMaximumAssigned(), getAgencyConstant(), ranges()

    • getAgencyConstant

      public Isbn getAgencyConstant()
      Called by constants that assignRangeConstant() returns (RANGE constants) in order to obtain the corresponding type of constant that assignAgencyConstant() returns (an AGENCY constant); in other words, called by a RANGE constant (i.e., a constant that returns RANGE when it calls getContext()) in order to obtain an AGENCY constant (i.e., a constant that returns AGENCY when it calls getContext()).

      Can be seen as effectively converting a constant that represents a range to one that represents an agency:

              Isbn nominallycovariantconstant = Isbn.ENGLISH_LANGUAGE_0__00_TO_19_RANGE;
	nominallycovariantconstant = nominallycovariantconstant.getAgencyConstant(); //now assigned to Isbn.ENGLISH_LANGUAGE_0

      

      

      Returns:
      

        

      • 
Returns the constant for the corresponding registration group when called by a constant that 
has a corresponding range instead of a corresponding registration group (i.e., the type returned when 
assignRangeConstant() is called: a RANGE constant).

        • 

      • 
Returns null when called by any other type of constant.

        • 

      

      

      

      • 

    • 

      

      getMaximumAssigned
      

      public int getMaximumAssigned()
      

      Called principally by constants returned by assignRangeConstant() 
(RANGE constants) in order to determine the number of prefixes available in a given range.

      

      

      Returns:
      

        

      • 
When called by a RANGE constant (i.e., the type of constant returned by assignRangeConstant()), 
returns an integer representing the number of prefixes available in the range. For example, either 
        Isbn.ENGLISH_LANGUAGE_0__00_TO_19_RANGE.getMaximumAssigned()

        
or
        Isbn.assignRangeConstant("0192816179").getMaximumAssigned()

        

returns 20.

        • 

      • 
If a constant is the type returned when assignAgencyConstant() 
is called (an AGENCY constant), its MAXIMUM_ASSIGNED attribute is set initially by the compiler to 0, and subsequently 
updated as a side effect each time that the constant's getComponent() 
method is called. The constant in question will return its current value should it call getMaximumAssigned(). 
The following declarations are equivalent:
        Isbn agencyconstant = Isbn.ENGLISH_LANGUAGE_0;
Isbn sameagencyconstant = Isbn.ENGLISH_LANGUAGE_0__00_TO_19_RANGE.getAgencyConstant();


        
If either variable calls getComponent(), one and the same 
MAXIMUM_ASSIGNED integer attribute is updated:
        agencyconstant.getComponent("9780007236084");
//both agencyconstant.getMaximumAssigned() and sameagencyconstant.getMaximumAssigned() now return 20
sameagencyconstant.getComponent("0552137529");
//both agencyconstant.getMaximumAssigned() and sameagencyconstant.getMaximumAssigned() now return 269
agencyconstant.getComponent("0140114157");
//both agencyconstant.getMaximumAssigned() and sameagencyconstant.getMaximumAssigned() return 20 again


        
The Isbn type can change the value of MAXIMUM_ASSIGNED at runtime for constants returned by 
assignAgencyConstant() (AGENCY constants), but never does so for 
constants returned by assignRangeConstant() (RANGE constants).

        • 

      • 
Constants that return Isbn.COMPONENT or Isbn.CONTEXT 
after calling getContext() return 0 when they call getMaximumAssigned().

        • 

      

      

      

      • 

    • 

      

      allComponentsAsArray
      

      public static String[][][] allComponentsAsArray​(String... isbns)
      

      Furnishes the different parts of one or more ISBNs as a multidimensional array.

      
An ISBN is discarded if its prefix cannot be inferred based on RangeMessage.xml.

      
If an ISBN causes a PoorISBNDataException to be 
thrown, allComponentsAsArray() handles the exception, 
prints a message to stderr, and discards the ISBN.

      
The value returned by allComponentsAsArray() is assigned to a variable as follows:
                              String[] isbns = {"0415083699","2738424155","3518576348"};
			String[][][] results = Isbn.allComponentsAsArray(isbns);
			//String[][][] results = Isbn.allComponentsAsArray("0415083699","2738424155","3518576348"); //varargs

      
Using the following syntax, the respective dimensions of the array produced by the above code 
can be accessed:

      

      

SYNTAX:


LENGTH:


Details:


      

      

results


3 



        

      • 
The length is equal to the number of parameters passed to allComponentsAsArray() (or to the length 
of the array object passed instead of varargs).

        • 

      • 
The value of the variable is all three dimensions of the array, which is to say the array object overall. 

        • 

      

      
      		

      

      

results[0]


13



        

      • 
The length is equal to the number of key/value pairs, which is only ever 13.

        • 

      • 
The value that the brackets operator returns is the array of key-value pairs located at the specified index.

        • 

          

        • 
results[1] would return the second array, which was generated when "2738424155" was processed.

          • 

        • 
results[3] would cause an ArrayIndexOutofBoundsException: the maximum index is 2, because there 
are three arrays. Each array has exactly 13 members, but they cannot be accessed unless the 
brackets operator is repeated.

          • 

        

      

      
      		

      

      

results[0][0]
      (optionally,
      results[0][0][0])

      		

2



        

      • 
The length is only ever equal to that of a key/value pair, which is to say 2.

        • 

      • 
The value that the second brackets operator returns is a key/value pair.

        • 

      • 
Furnishing the argument 0 to a third (succeeding) brackets operator only ever causes a key to 
be returned, and furnishing the argument 1 to a third (succeeding) brackets operator only ever causes 
a value to be returned.

        • 

      
      		

      

      
The very last of the above points is paramount. The only two possible values to pass to the 
third brackets operator without causing a runtime exception are 0 (e.g., 0 % x, where x is greater 
than 0) and 1 (e.g., 1 % x, where x is greater than one).

      
In order to read the String values, a loop ultimately needs to take account of at least 
two array dimensions regardless of whether more than one parameter was passed to allComponentsAsArray(), 
or whether there was only a single parameter:
      
                        for (int i = 0;i < results.length;i++)
				   for (int j = 0;j < results[i].length;j++) {
				   System.out.print(results[i][j][0] + " is ");
				   System.out.println(results[i][j][1]);}
                        

      Above, a second inner loop would have iterated over only two Strings, 
which already were different in kind to one another: the one assigned the 
even index was required by the code as a key, while that assigned the odd index was required 
by it as a value.

      
Not each and every conceivable iteration requires an inner loop in order to retrieve data:
      
                        for (int i = 0;i < results.length;i++) {
				System.out.println(results[i][3][1]);
				System.out.println(results[i][0][1]);
			}
				   //Prints:
				   //9780  //the prefix of the first parameter ("0415083699")
				   //English language
				   //9782  //the prefix of the second parameter ("2738424155")
				   //French language
				   //9783  //the prefix of the third parameter ("3518576348")
				   //German language
				   
                                   

      The index of the PREFIX key/value pair already was known to be 3, and 
the index of the AGENCY_NAME key/value pair already was known to be 0. The mapping 
of the key/value pairs to array indexes is given below.
      

      

      Parameters:
      

      isbns - One or more International Standard Book Numbers.

        

      • 
ISBNs that cause assignAgencyConstant() 
to return UNKNOWN when passed as its parameter are discarded, and 
a message is written to stderr.

        • 

      • 
ISBNs that cause a PoorISBNDataException to be thrown 
are discarded.

        • 

      

      Returns:
      

      Returns a three-dimensional array.
      

        

      • 
The size of the first array dimension is equal to the number of parameters passed, or the 
size of the array object passed as a parameter instead of varargs. Each element is an 
array of key/value pairs. The indexes and corresponding keys are as follows:
        

        IndexKeyIndexKey
        

        0AGENCY_NAME1Agency constant
        

        2CHECK_DIGIT3PREFIX
        

        4PREFIX_OLD5PUBLICATION_ELEMENT
        

        6PUBLICATION_ELEMENT_EXTENT7PUBLICATION_ELEMENT_SIZE
        

        8Qualified registrant element9REGISTRANT_ELEMENT
        

        10REGISTRANT_ELEMENT_EXTENT11REGISTRANT_ELEMENT_SIZE
        

        12Range constant
        

        

        • 

      • 
The size of the second array dimension is only ever 13. Each element is an array consisting of 
one key and one value. The integer indexes are as follows:
        

        0Key
        

        1Value
        

        

        • 

      • 
The size of the third array dimension is only ever 2. The third array dimension stores the 
String data itself: the first element is a key, and the second element is a value.

        • 

      

      
The first dimension of the array is accessed by using the name of the variable to which it is 
assigned followed by the brackets operator and the index of the desired array of key/value 
pairs (e.g. results[0] for the first array).

      
The second dimension of the array is accessed by using the name of the variable to which it is 
assigned followed by the brackets operator and the index number of the desired array of key/value 
pairs, followed by a second brackets operator and the index number (0-12) of the desired key/value 
pair (e.g. results[0][0] for the first key/value pair in the first array).

      
The third dimension of the array is accessed by using the name of the variable to which it is 
assigned followed by the brackets operator and the index number of the desired array of key/value 
pairs, followed by a second brackets operator and the index number (0-12) of the desired key/value pair, 
followed by a third (and final) brackets operator and the index number of either the key (index 0) or 
the value (index 1): for example, results[0][0][1] for the value of the 
first key/value pair in the first array.
      

      See Also:
      

      allComponentsMinKeys(String isbn), 
allComponentsAddedKeys(String isbn),

      allComponentsAsJson
      

      public static String allComponentsAsJson​(String... isbns)
      

      Calls allComponentsMinKeys() and subsequently produces a 
String in JSON format; if multiple parameters are passed, a JSON string is produced for each. By 
default, a newline character is included only after the closing brace of the JSON string that is 
produced.

      
An ISBN is discarded if its prefix cannot be inferred based on RangeMessage.xml.

      
If an ISBN causes a PoorISBNDataException to be 
thrown, allComponentsAsJson() handles the exception, 
prints a message to stderr, and discards the ISBN.
      

      

      Parameters:
      

      isbns - One or more International Standard Book Numbers in either 10-digit or 13-digit format.

      

        

      • 
If the first parameter passed is the String literal "true" or its equivalent, the output will 
contain newlines after each key/value pair. An overloaded version of the allComponentsAsJson()  
method (allComponentsAsJson(boolean newlines,String... isbn)) 
permits the caller to explicitly turn newlines off and on.

        • 

      • 
Otherwise, the output will contain newline characters only after each JSON string's closing brace.

        • 

      • 
ISBNs that cause assignAgencyConstant() 
to return UNKNOWN when passed as its parameter are discarded, and 
a message is written to stderr.

        • 

      • 
ISBNs that cause a PoorISBNDataException to be thrown 
are discarded, and a message is written to stderr.

        • 

      

      Returns:
      

      A String object in JSON format, or a concatenation of two or more String 
objects in JSON format, all of which contain the following keys:
      

      

AGENCY_NAME


Agency constant


CHECK_DIGIT


      

      

PREFIX


PREFIX_OLD


PUBLICATION_ELEMENT


      

      

PUBLICATION_ELEMENT_EXTENT


PUBLICATION_ELEMENT_SIZE


Qualified registrant element


      

      

REGISTRANT_ELEMENT


REGISTRANT_ELEMENT_EXTENT


REGISTRANT_ELEMENT_SIZE


      

      

Range constant


      

      

      See Also:

      allComponentsMinKeys
      

      public static TreeMap<String,​String> allComponentsMinKeys​(String isbn)
      

      Furnishes a sorted map containing the corresponding data for the International Standard Book Number passed as an argument; 
omits two of the keys produced when allComponentsAddedKeys() is called instead.

      

        

      • 
allComponentsMinKeys()  produces the same set of keys each time that it is called

        • 

      • 
allComponentsAddedKeys() produces an additional two keys the names of which are 
assigned at runtime, and can be called if one is planning to pass an arbitrary AGENCY or RANGE 
constant's String equivalent to the TreeMap class's get() method later.

        • 

      

      
Called by the Isbn type's main() method.
      

      

      Parameters:
      

      isbn - An International Standard Book Number, in either 10-digit or 13-digit format.
      

      Returns:
      

      Returns a TreeMap containing the following keys:
      

      

AGENCY_NAME


Agency constant


CHECK_DIGIT


      

      

PREFIX


PREFIX_OLD


PUBLICATION_ELEMENT


      

      

PUBLICATION_ELEMENT_EXTENT


PUBLICATION_ELEMENT_SIZE


Qualified registrant element


      

      

REGISTRANT_ELEMENT


REGISTRANT_ELEMENT_EXTENT


REGISTRANT_ELEMENT_SIZE


      

      

Range constant


      

      

      Throws:
      

      Throws - a CannotInferPrefixException if UNKNOWN 
is returned upon a call to assignAgencyConstant().

        

      • 
UNKNOWN is returned by assignAgencyConstant() 
if the ISBN's prefix cannot be inferred based on RangeMessage.xml.

        • 

      • 
In the same circumstances, allComponentsAsJson()  
and allComponentsAsArray() discard the ISBN 
and print a message to stderr rather than throw an exception.

        • 

          

        • 
allComponentsAddedKeys(), by contrast, throws a 
CannotInferPrefixException.

          • 

        

      

      See Also:
      

      allComponentsAsArray(String... isbns), 
allComponentsAsJson(String... isbns),

      allComponentsAddedKeys
      

      public static TreeMap<String,​String> allComponentsAddedKeys​(String isbn)
      

      Furnishes a sorted map containing the corresponding data for the International Standard Book Number passed as an argument.

      

        

      • 
allComponentsMinKeys() produces the same set of keys each time that it is called

        • 

      • 
allComponentsAddedKeys() produces an additional two keys the names of which are 
assigned at runtime, and can be called if one is planning to pass an arbitrary AGENCY or RANGE 
constant's String equivalent to the TreeMap class's get() method later.

        • 

      

      

      Parameters:
      

      isbn - An International Standard Book Number, in either 10-digit or 13-digit format.
      

      Returns:
      

      A TreeMap the keys of which are the names of the relevant constants, plus one called "Agency constant"
for the name of the ISBN's corresponding type, one called "Range constant" for the range in which the ISBN 
falls within its registrant group, one called "Qualified registrant element" concatenating the prefix  
and the registrant element, and also one consisting of the name of the ISBN's corresponding AGENCY constant.

      
To put it differently, the keys in tabular form are as follows (the position in the sorted order of those 
in brackets shall vary):

      

      

[AGENCY constant identifier]


[RANGE constant identifier]


Agency Constant


      

      

AGENCY_NAME


CHECK_DIGIT


PREFIX


      

      

PREFIX_OLD


PUBLICATION_ELEMENT


PUBLICATION_ELEMENT_EXTENT


      

      

PUBLICATION_ELEMENT_SIZE


Qualified registrant element


REGISTRANT_ELEMENT


      

      

REGISTRANT_ELEMENT_EXTENT


REGISTRANT_ELEMENT_SIZE


Range constant


      

      

      Throws:
      

      Throws - a CannotInferPrefixException if UNKNOWN 
is returned upon a call to assignAgencyConstant().

        

      • 
UNKNOWN is returned by assignAgencyConstant() 
if the ISBN's prefix cannot be inferred based on RangeMessage.xml.

        • 

      • 
In the same circumstances, allComponentsAsJson()  
and allComponentsAsArray() discard the ISBN 
and print a message to stderr rather than throw an exception.

        • 

          

        • 
allComponentsMinKeys(), by contrast, throws a 
CannotInferPrefixException.

          • 

        

      

      See Also:

      getRegistrantElementExtentAsInt
      

      public static int getRegistrantElementExtentAsInt​(String isbn)
      

      Accepts an ISBN in 10-digit or 13-digit format as input and returns an int indicating  
the length of the range to which the registrant element belongs; in effect, the maximum number 
of registrants who can be assigned to the range in which the registrant element of the ISBN that 
is to hand falls. For example:
                              Isbn.getRegistrantElementExtentAsInt("0684717611"); //returns 44
			Isbn.getRegistrantElement("0684717611"); // returns "684"
.
      

      

      Parameters:
      

      isbn - An International Standard Book Number in either 10-digit or 13-digit format.
      

      Returns:
      

      An int indicating the length of the range to which the registrant 
element belongs.

      getComponent
      

      public String getComponent​(String isbn)
      

      A method overridden by constants returned by assignAgencyConstant() 
(AGENCY constants) and constants that return Isbn.COMPONENT when they call getContext() 
(COMPONENT constants).
      

      

      Parameters:
      

      isbn - An International Standard Book Number, in either 10-digit or 13-digit format.
      

      Returns:
      

        

      • 
Constants returned by assignAgencyConstant() (AGENCY constants) return a String that 
concatenates the agency prefix and the registrant prefix (except for Isbn.UNKNOWN, which returns 
an empty String); also, when AGENCY constants (i.e., constants returned by assignAgencyConstant()) 
call getComponent(), the constant's MAXIMUM_ASSIGNED attribute is calculated and is subsequently 
set as a side effect.

        • 

      • 
Isbn.PREFIX returns a String consisting of the agency's prefix preceded by the EAN/UCC prefix

        • 

      • 
Isbn.PREFIX_OLD returns a String consisting of the agency's prefix without the EAN/UCC prefix that 13-digit ISBNs incorporate.

        • 

      • 
Isbn.AGENCY_NAME returns a String consisting of the name that occurred in RangeMessage.xml's Agency element

        • 

      • 
Isbn.REGISTRANT_ELEMENT returns a String consisting only of the part of the ISBN that identifies the publisher
 (i.e., the registrant prefix).

        • 

      • 
Isbn.PUBLICATION_ELEMENT returns a String comprising the portion of the ISBN between the registrant 
element and the check digit.

        • 

      • 
Isbn.CHECK_DIGIT returns a String comprising only the check digit. 
If the parameter was a 10-digit ISBN, the check digit returned is 
the check digit calculated for use in 13-digit ISBNs.

        • 

      • 
Isbn.REGISTRANT_ELEMENT_SIZE returns a String indicating the number of digits in (length of) 
the registrant element (publisher prefix).

        • 

      • 
Isbn.REGISTRANT_ELEMENT_EXTENT returns a String indicating the length of the range to which 
the registrant element belongs: in effect, the maximum number of registrants who can be assigned  
to the range in which the registrant element of the ISBN that is to hand falls.

        • 

      • 
Isbn.PUBLICATION_ELEMENT_SIZE returns a String indicating the number of digits in (length of) 
the publication element.

        • 

      • 
Isbn.PUBLICATION_ELEMENT_EXTENT returns a String that in effect indicates the maximum number 
of times the ISBN's registrant element/publisher prefix can be used.

        • 

      • 
Isbn.UNKNOWN returns an empty String after calling getComponent().

        • 

      • 
Elements returned by assignRangeConstant() (RANGE constants) 
return null after calling getComponent().

        • 

      • 
Isbn.AGENCY, Isbn.RANGE, Isbn.COMPONENT, and Isbn.CONTEXT return null after calling 
getComponent().

        • 

      

      Throws:
      

      Throws - a CannotInferPrefixException if UNKNOWN 
is returned upon a call to assignAgencyConstant() and 
the caller is a constant that returns COMPONENT when it calls 
getContext().

        

      • 
UNKNOWN is returned by assignAgencyConstant() 
if the ISBN's prefix cannot be inferred based on RangeMessage.xml.

        • 

      • 
Internally, the Isbn type's API preempts most calls to getComponent() that 
ultimately would cause it to throw a CannotInferPrefixException.

        •

      isValid
      

      public static boolean isValid​(String isbn)
      

      Validates an International Standard Book Number.

      

        

      • 
The isValid() method is suitable for screening data 
that consists of ISBNs for typos.

        • 

      • 
Only software expressly dedicated to processing ISBNs that have yet to be assigned 
need be used in order to determine whether an ISBN is de jure valid.

        • 

      

      
This method is never called internally by the Isbn type and is included for completeness. The 
Isbn type's other methods all call isbnThirteen() before proceeding 
to do anything.
      

      

      Parameters:
      

      isbn - An International Standard Book Number in either 10-digit or 13-digit format.
      

      Returns:
      

      Returns true if the ISBN is valid.

      
Returns true when a valid ISBN in 10-digit format is passed as its parameter, and 
also when its equivalent in 13-digit format is passed as its parameter.

      
Returns false if the ISBN is not valid; returns false and writes a message to stderr
if the ISBN is missing out digits or (for 13-digit ISBNs) does not begin with 978 or 979.
      

      See Also:
      

      isbnThirteen(String isbn), 
CHECK_DIGIT
      

      

      

      • 

    • 

      

      isbnThirteen
      

      public static String isbnThirteen​(String isbn)
      

      Called each and every time the Isbn type begins performing an operation that concerns  
one or more of an ISBN's components.

      
The isbnThirteen() and isValid() methods can be invoked 
by means of the Isbn type, and respectively convert a 10-digit ISBN to one in 13-digit 
format or determine whether an ISBN in either format is valid.
      

      

      Parameters:
      

      isbn - An International Standard Book Number in either 10-digit or 13-digit format. 
The isbnThirteen() method at no point attempts to validate the ISBN passed to it as its 
argument: it discards the check digit if the ISBN was passed to it in 10-digit format.
      

      Returns:
      

      A String comprising an International Standard Book Number in 13-digit format. If the ISBN 
passed as a parameter is in 10-digit format, a 13-digit ISBN is nonetheless returned: the 
isbnThirteen() method will have recalculated the check digit.
      

      Throws:
      

      Throws - a PoorISBNDataException in case of missing or 
extraneous digits, or if an ISBN in 13-digit format does not begin with either 978 or 979.
      

      See Also:
      

      isValid(String isbn)

      main
      

      public static void main​(String... argv)
      

      Calls allComponentsMinKeys() and prints an iteration over 
the result to standard output.

      
The main() method is invoked from the command line as follows:
      
                        java io.sourceforge.curtthomas.Isbn 3458329021 9780863698774


      
If the Isbn command is not followed by at least one ISBN number, the main() method will 
send a message to standard output rather than continue running.
      

      

      Parameters:
      

      argv - One or more International Standard Book Numbers in either 13-digit or 10-digit format, delimited on the command line by a space character or, from code, by a comma.

        

      • 
The Isbn type is intended for use with existing ISBNs. Passing ISBNs as parameters that have 
never been assigned to an item as a consequence of a decision by a publisher or an agency could cause main(), 
allComponentsAsArray(), allComponentsMinKeys(), 
allComponentsAddedKeys(), allComponentsAsJson(), 
or the JsonIsbn class to throw a runtime exception.

        • 

      

      See Also:
      

      JsonIsbn.main(String... argv)
